<P>
BRIEFLY: BANKING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 T-Bill Rates Fall: The Treasury Department sold $12.4 billion of new 
three-month bills at an average discount rate of 4.31%, down from 4.50% last 
week. Another $12.4 billion of new six-month bills was sold at an average 
discount rate of 4.71%, down from 4.94%.The three-month bill rate was the 
lowest since they sold for 4.20% on June 27, and the six-month bill rate was 
the lowest since they averaged 4.60% the same day. The new discount rates 
understate the actual return to investors: 4.42% for three-month bills, with a 
$10,000 bill selling for $9,891.10, and 4.89% for a six-month bill selling for 
$9,761.90. The discount rate reflects the price discount received when 
government securities are purchased at less than face value. T-Bill Auction 
</P>
