<HEADLINE>
<P>
A GIANT LEAP FOR STRAWBERRY; BASEBALL: SAN FRANCISCO IS 8-0 SINCE THE FORMER 
DODGER OUTFIELDER JOINED THE TEAM. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Darryl Strawberry and the San Francisco Giants have proved to be a winning 
combination. 
</P>
<P>
 "He's definitely picked us up," Manager Dusty Baker said Sunday after the 
Giants beat the Montreal Expos, 6-4. It was San Francisco's eighth consecutive 
victory -- all since Strawberry joined the club. 
</P>
<P>
 "We knew he could help us and that we could help him. He's just happy to be 
playing again. 
</P>
<P>
 "When you see such exuberance from a a veteran, it has a positive influence on 
the club." 
</P>
<P>
 Strawberry has helped the Giants make up five games on the first-place Dodgers 
in the National League West. San Francisco began play Monday in third place, 4 
1/2 games back. 
</P>
<P>
 Strawberry's performance with the Giants is being compared to Fred McGriff's 
effect upon Atlanta last season after the first baseman joined the Braves 
following a trade from San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
 McGriff sparked the Braves to a 51-17 record after June 20, when they trailed 
the Giants by 7 1/2 games, and beat San Francisco by one game for the division 
title. 
</P>
<P>
 Can Strawberry do the same for San Francisco? 
</P>
<P>
 "He's a big presence behind Barry (Bonds) and Matt (Williams)," Baker said. 
"And he's getting big hits, too. 
</P>
<P>
 "We'd like to get back in the race as soon as possible. We can't see the light 
at the end of the tunnel yet, but it's not high-noon either." 
</P>
<P>
 Rookie William VanLandingham pitched no-hit ball through 7 1/3 innings, 
leaving after Lenny Webster doubled and Mike Lansing walked. Rod Beck got four 
outs for his 20th save. 
</P>
<P>
 Williams led the Giants with a two-run homer, his 34th, in the first against 
Jeff Fassero. Todd Benzinger contributed a two-run double, while Bonds and 
Strawberry each drove in a run. 
</P>
<P>
 Bonds went 10 for 19 in the series with two two-homer games and seven RBIs. 
Strawberry went nine for 17 with two homers, including a grand slam, and seven 
RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
 "All I wanted to do when I started playing again was get comfortable," 
Strawberry said. "It's coming. It's almost there." 
</P>
<P>
 The Giants got 47 hits in posting their first four-game sweep at Montreal 
since Aug. 11-14, 1975. 
</P>
<P>
 The victory also gave them an eight-game winning streak for the first time 
since July 20-Aug. 1, 1991, when they won 11 in a row. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're still in third place, there's a long way to go," Williams said. "We 
need to keep winning and put pressure on the other teams. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's not a coincidence that we've been winning since (Strawberry) has been 
here, but that's because of the way he's swinging the bat. One or two guys 
can't do it alone everyday. Everybody's got to contribute." 
</P>
<P>
 Strawberry entered the series with only an infield hit in 11 at-bats in his 
first four games at Candlestick Park. 
</P>
<P>
 Before signing with the Giants, Strawberry was "seconds away" from signing 
with Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
 "I liked Kevin (Malone, the Expo general manager) a lot," said Strawberry, who 
has a history of success hitting at Olympic Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was difficult to choose. I continued to think about it all that night 
(before signing). 
</P>
<P>
 "But who knows what the future holds? I'll be a free agent at the end of the 
year." 
</P>
<P>
 Strawberry began the season as a member of the Dodgers, but during the first 
week of April admitted he had a substance abuse problem and was admitted to the 
Betty Ford Rehabilitation Clinic in Palm Desert, Calif. Later, he was released 
by the Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
 "I was ready to retire and be with my family after the Dodgers released me," 
Strawberry said. 
</P>
<P>
 That's when Baker called and convinced him to play for the Giants. 
</P>
<P>
 "Baseball is more fun now that my head is clear," Strawberry said. "Life is 
better now than I ever thought it could be." 
</P>
</TEXT>
