<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: POMONA; MAN SHOT WHILE 
WATCHING WORLD CUP FINAL ON TV 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 43-year-old Pomona man remained in critical condition Monday after being 
shot in the face during a home robbery while he watched the World Cup soccer 
final on television Sunday.  
</P>
<P>
 Police said three suspects were arrested and are believed to be members of an 
Asian gang.Officers said the victim, whose name was not released, also is 
Asian, as are the people who were with him at the house in the 1000 block of 
South Waters Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
 Several men, women and children were watching the game when the robbers 
entered the home, said Pomona Police Lt. Rick Mackey.  
</P>
<P>
 One of the people in the house retrieved a shotgun and in a tussle it 
discharged, hitting suspect Rathana Phung, 19, of Santa Ana, police said. One 
of the other suspects allegedly shot the 43-year-old man in the face at 
point-blank range with a handgun. Police said they were investigating who shot 
the man. 
</P>
<P>
 Suspects Map Eam, 20, of Long Beach, and a 16-year-old boy from Downey took 
Phung to Pomona Valley Hospital Medical Center, where they were arrested. 
</P>
<P>
 All three were booked on suspicion of attempted murder.  
</P>
<P>
 Police were uncertain whether the suspects knew the victims and were 
investigating whether rival gang members were in the house during the attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA071994-0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 062023 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
July 19, 1994, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 2; Column 3; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
118 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: POMONA; TESTING ORDERED 
FOR KILLER OF WITNESS IN MURDER CASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A judge ruled Monday that a gang member who killed a teen-ager to keep him 
from testifying in the murder trial of a "home boy" must undergo 90 days of 
evaluation before he is sentenced. 
</P>
<P>
 Patrick Ignacio Contreras was a juvenile when he killed 14-year-old Eduardo 
Samaniego on Aug. 17, 1992. Superior Court Judge George Trammell was required 
by law to send Contreras, now 19, to the California Youth Authority for the 
diagnostic evaluation. Contreras, due for sentencing Oct. 14, entered a 
negotiated plea to a second-degree murder charge after Samaniego's parents 
refused to allow their daughter to testify. Contreras is expected to get 20 
years to life. The defendant in the first case was convicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
